## 11. Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Choice | Rationale |
|----------|--------|-----------|
| Orchestration framework | LangGraph | Deterministic control flow; native state management; parallel execution; human checkpoints; LangSmith integration. Avoids custom boilerplate. |
| LLM | Claude Sonnet 4.6 | Strong tool_use for structured output; large context window for demand history; reliable JSON generation |
| Number of scenarios | 3 (Conservative / Moderate / Aggressive) | Cognitive load research: 3 options is the maximum a planner can meaningfully evaluate. More forces artificial differentiation or decision paralysis. |
| Parallel agent execution | Demand Decomposition + Supply Constraint in parallel | Fully independent. Reduces end-to-end latency ~40% vs. sequential. |
| Financial calculation | Deterministic math + LLM narration only | Financial projections must be fully traceable (SOX compliance). LLM never generates numbers — only formats narrative around pre-computed figures. |
| DB access mode | Read-only to TenantDB | Eliminates risk of agent errors corrupting production data. Write-back uses approved Blue Ridge APIs only. |
| Human-in-the-loop | Mandatory for all policy changes (POC #1 = Autonomy Level 2) | Trust must be earned over multiple production cycles before any automation is considered. |
| SQL vs. KG | SQL for POC #1; KG introduced in Phase 3 | KG adds power but adds infrastructure complexity. POC validates core agent logic first with SQL. KG is additive — no agent rewrites required when it's added. |
| "Everything is an MCP tool" | All data sources wrapped as MCP tools | Adding a new data source means adding one tool registration, not modifying agent logic. This is the composability principle. |

